      <div xml:id="NA79-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu pirivuṇarntu vēṟupaṭṭa talaimakaḷ tōḻikkuc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE, who was changed after understanding that [HE] would separate, said to [her] confidante.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA79">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            ciṟainā ḷīṅkai yuṟainaṉi tiraḷvī</l>
<l>            kūṉār naṉmaṉaik kuṟuntoṭi makaḷir</l>
<l>            maṇalāṭu kaḻaṅki ṉaṟaimicait tāa</l>
<l>            mērtara luṟṟa viyakkaruṅ kavalaip</l>
<l>            pirintōr vantup puṇarap puṇarntōr </l>
<l>            pirital cūḻtali ṉariyatu muṇṭō</l>
<l>            veṉṟunāṅ kūṟik kāmañ cepputuñ</l>
<l>            ceppātu viṭiṉē yuyiroṭum vantaṉ</l>
<l>            ṟamma vāḻi tōḻi {nammil}</l>
<l>            yātaṉiṟ ṟavirkkuvaṅ kātalar celavē. </l>
<l rend="indent4">            yātaṉiṉ ṟavirkkuvaṅ kollō</l>
<l rend="indent4">            nōtaku muḷḷaṅ kātalar celavē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>“Is it difficult too, when we consider, to separate</l>
<l>those that are united, for them to be [re-]united,</l>
<l rend="indent">when the one who separated has come from the crossroads difficult</l>
<l rend="indent">to march, which had the bringing of beauty<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ēr taral uṟṟa</term>: here the text does look suspiciously out of order. Even if we read the <term xml:lang="ta">ēr</term> against the formulaic usage not as the verbal root 'to rise', but as a noun 'beauty', it is still hard to reconcile the co-presence of <term xml:lang="ta">taral</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">uṟṟa</term>.</note>, where the dripping<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uṟai</term> is explained by T.V.G. as the honey drops (rather nectar drops) inside the blossoms.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent3">very round blossom of the mimosa<note place="foot">T.V.G. explains the <term xml:lang="ta">īṅkai</term> to be a palm tree.</note> closed by day(?)<note place="foot">The strange phrase <term xml:lang="ta">ciṟai nāḷ</term> is explained by T.V.G. as closing the blossoms during daytime.</note> spread</l>
<l rend="indent2">on the rocky heights like the Molucca-beans spread in play in the sand</l>
<l rend="indent">by women with small bracelets from the good houses with curvy bark?”<note place="foot">Here we have the choice between two unsatisfactory readings, <term xml:lang="ta">kūṉ nār</term> as above or <term xml:lang="ta">kūrai</term> "roof", and both moreover look like reciprocal glosses: good houses thatched with curvy bark would make good sense, but we are landed with an ellipsis either way: good houses with roofs or with bark.</note>,</l>
<l>[thus] we shall speak and talk of desire.</l>
<l>If we give in without speaking,</l>
<l rend="indent4">it will have come [to pass] along with [our] life.<note place="foot">Modal usage of the p.a.: "it (the separation) will have come [to pass] along with our life". Note that this understanding can integrate the instrumental <term xml:lang="ta">uyir-oṭu</term>; T.V.G. reads another ellipsis ('[trouble] will have come also for [our] life'), and this means an instrumental for a dative.</note></l>
<l>Alas, oh friend,</l>
<l>how do we prevent [our] lover from going?</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
